DCAMM’S Mission

The Division of Capital Asset Management and Maintenance (DCAMM) is responsible for capital planning, project delivery, property management, and real estate services for the Commonwealth. We are stewards of the Commonwealth’s assets. We care for the people of our state and future of our planet.

Our job is to work with our state agencies to create and manage forward-thinking, sustainable buildings to meet the needs of our citizens. We are partners with our agencies to help them meet their strategic needs with fiscally responsible building and real estate solutions. We support the growth of our economy and actively engage with our private sector partners to make it easier to do business with the Commonwealth and improve access and opportunity.

Our agency oversees $2 billion in capital programs and projects. We manage 5.5 million square feet of state buildings and assist agencies in the sound management of their properties. We are responsible for all real estate activities, including leasing, acquisition, and disposition, managing over 100 transactions each year.

Position Summary

The Deputy Director of Human Resources at DCAMM is a senior member of the HR Team who will take a leadership role in helping to formulate how we will deliver HR services in an era of major change in the workplace and what it will look like in the future. This position will also oversee all human resources operations including, but not limited to, recruitment, employee classification and compensation, labor relations, training and learning development, payroll processing, workers’ compensation, and benefit administration. The Deputy Director also collaborates in developing and implementing strategies to enhance DCAMM’s ongoing commitment to diversify our workforce. In the absence of the Director of Human Resources, the Deputy Director will oversee the management of the unit.

Major Responsibility Areas

Plans, organizes, and directs, in partnership with the Director, the day-to-day activities of DCAMM’s HR Department, including payroll, benefits (health insurance, FMLA, Workers’ Compensation, EILB, etc.), HR Programs (Performance Recognition, etc.) and hiring;

Takes a leadership role in a major new initiative to partner with appropriate DCAMM staff and vendors, as needed, to begin the process of digitizing and modernizing HR including, but not limited to, personnel files, forms, processes, etc.;

Works with all DCAMM units to develop effective recruitment strategies for filling DCAMM vacancies, including highly technical positions related to building engineering, design, maintenance and construction management; additionally, cultivating relationships with area colleges and universities to recruit talent for our entry level positions as well as offering internships and co-op opportunities for prospective future full time employment;

Develops and implements strategies to attract and retain a more diverse work force, and to enhance DCAMM’s standing as a Model Employer for employees with disabilities consistent with the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA);

Oversees the agency’s efforts to timely address employee classification and compensation issues as they arise, including MEPA, for union and management personnel;

Works closely with DCAMM’s Labor Relations Manager (in consultation with A&F and HRD) on matters related to DCAMM union employees, or on matters dealing with broader collective bargaining issues;

Serves as the primary contact with HRD on efforts to roll-out enhanced HR/CMS functionality (including time and attendance module);

Oversees DCAMM HR’s continuing efforts to provide excellent customer service to DCAMM employees, including sensitive issues and working to resolve them in a timely fashion;

Works with our training manager to provide cost-effective training and professional development opportunities for DCAMM staff that will support DCAMM’s Mission;

Oversees process and technical assistance to managers and staff regarding performance management systems (ACES/MassPerform and EPRS);

Serves as the agency’s liaison with the State Ethics Commission for Statement of Financial Interest forms (SFI).

MINIMUM ENTRANCE REQUIREMENTS:

Applicants must have at least (A) six (6) years of full-time or, equivalent part-time, professional, administrative, supervisory, or managerial experience in business administration, business management, public administration, public management, clinical administration or clinical management of which (B) at least two (2) years must have been in a project management, supervisory or managerial capacity or (C) any equivalent combination of the required experience and substitutions below.

Substitutions:

I. A certificate in a relevant or related field may be substituted for one (1) year of the required (A) experience.

II. A Bachelor’s degree in a related field may be substituted for two (2) years of the required (A) experience.

III. A Graduate degree in a related field may be substituted for three (3) years of the required (A) experience.

IV. A Doctorate degree in a related field may be substituted for four (4) years of the required (A) experience.

An Equal Opportunity / Affirmative Action Employer. Females, minorities, veterans, and persons with disabilities are strongly encouraged to apply.

